Czech discovery: a substance that also affects the 'insufficiency' of HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the organism.
The main advantage of an improved substance is that it also works on viruses that have already gained immunity against medicines.
In some cases, this outweighs the fact that the compound on the normal variant of the virus does not act as strongly as some of the medicines already available.
AIDS has not yet been cured.
However, patients may significantly extend the life of a mixture of medicines that prevent the proliferation of HIV in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, the incomplete suppression of the virus results in the development of so-called resistent viruses against which medicines are already ineffective.
The work of experts from the three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from the University of Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called meta-carborates have an effect on the protein responsible for multiplying the HIV virus.
Metallocarborates are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all medicines used today, so they can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists come up with new “better” compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of their molecular mechanism of binding to viral protein.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-wall cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case a cobalt.
Deceptive and resistant virus
HIV protease is a protein of HIV that is necessary for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV, the protease caused by HIV fission would not result in mature infectious viral particles.
When we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, scientists explain in the press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In the work published in the scientific journal Journal of Medical Chemistry scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is further systematically amended.
A little weaker but more reliable
The effect of this series of HIV protease substances has been tested in the test tube and against its resistant (resistent) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metalcarborates on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as that of the clinically used drugs, but does not lose its effect for resistant alternatives to which medicines are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and also its other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical adaptations thus makes interesting compounds for further research towards the design of effective anti-HIV drugs, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the laboratory of Structural biology of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
