75% of working mothers have maternal problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially in women of younger years who wish to have a child.
This is the result of a study by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute of Women in Spanish Women.
The study was attended by 9.737 women aged 15 to 75 and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities on the labour market due to motherhood.
The study stresses that at the beginning of the partnership there are many differences in views on the number of children depending on whether they work or not, and also on the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside their home are working part-time or have no stable work, start living with their partner sooner, before giving birth to their first child and overall have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, partnering and motherhood are delaying and having fewer offspring.
"Women from 35 to 49 years of age with stable employment have the first child on average 3,7 years from the start of coexist with a partner. This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted more to their stable employment and therefore had to postpone the coexistence of children as well.
The type of profession also has a strong impact on motherhood, although it has a minor impact on the start of co-operation with the partner", explains Margarita Delgado, who is engaged in research in CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage and the birth of a child is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age when women get married and have their first child.
Differences are also between women of the same generation.
For example, in a 35-49-year-old group, women with basic and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 or 32.1.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women get married and give birth to the first child before they find stable employment, while women with secondary or high education are acting the opposite way to get stable employment, before marriage and the birth of the first child", says Delgado.
